Establishing alternative care sites will help address surge in the response to COVID-19.
A local surge in the need for medical care may require jurisdictions to establish alternative (or alternate) care sites (ACS), which are intended to allow healthcare providers to provide care in non-traditional environments, such as converted public buildings or mobile field medical units.1
This guidance provides critical infection prevention and control (IPC) considerations for ACS and is intended to supplement existing ACS plans (created by jurisdictions as part of pandemic planning).
The following information is for ACS providing care to adult patients with confirmed COVID-19, but the patient:
Does not require the level of care available at an acute care hospital, and
Nursing home residents who have COVID-19 and need to be moved out of the facility
People with COVID-19 in the general population who cannot return to their place of residence for social reasons (e.g., there are elderly relatives in the home)
Patients with COVID-19 who are currently hospitalized but can be discharged to a lower level of care
People with COVID-19 who are currently experiencing homelessness and cannot be discharged to a congregate setting
Tier two: ACS houses a cohort of patients who require some level of assistance (e.g., help with ADLs or medications) and who need a closer level of monitoring than patients in tier one. These patients may be better suited in a facility that has an open layout (e.g., school gymnasium) to allow limited numbers of healthcare personnel to more easily monitor their status.
This guidance does not address a third tier of ACS that would provide more advanced care to patients (e.g., continuous IV therapy) or care for both confirmed and suspected COVID-19 patients. These scenarios would require additional IPC and staffing considerations.  For example, if the ACS provided care to both confirmed and suspected COVID-19 patients planning would need to address  maintaining physical separation between the different patient cohorts and assigning dedicate personnel to work in each area.
This guidance identifies some key considerations for IPC in ACS. However, it does not address other important aspects of ACS, including patient transportation to and from nearby healthcare facilities. Jurisdictions should consider how close the ACS is to nearby healthcare facilities, including acute care hospitals, and may need to have agreements in place with surrounding healthcare facilities regarding patient transfer.
