Chinese Communist Party general secretary Xi Jinping warned that China was facing a 'grave situation'.[20][21] He held a Party Politburo meeting which promised resources and experts for treatment and supplies to Hubei[106] as more and more cases of the viral infection, mostly exported from Wuhan were confirmed in other cities in Hubei[14] and multiple parts in mainland China.[107] On 29 January, Tibet announced its first confirmed case, a male who traveled from Wuhan to Lhasa by rail on 22–24 January[108] which marked that the virus spread to all parts of mainland China.[14][15][16]
At the end of December 2019, Henan Province announced the suspension of passenger trains to and from Wuhan. In early January 2020, the local government of Henan Province with its complete disinfection measures, effective and intensive publicity, a strong awareness of epidemic prevention and quarantine among the people, the setting up of return spots at the village entrance and even the use of garbage trucks, the digging of trenches to block roads connecting Hubei and the hanging of slogans such as "return home with sickness is to dishonor your parents." #抄河南的作业 (literally: 'copy Henan's homework') became a trending Weibo topic hashtag.[110][111][112]
However, cutting the roads off without authorization is illegal in mainland China as Xinhua and the Public Security Ministry pointed out.[113][114] The Ministry of Transport asked the local governments to take the principle of "block one, not three (Chinese: 一断三不断)", that is, to block the virus from spreading, but not to block roads, traffic and Internet access, the transportation of emergency supplies and the transportation of essential goods.[115]
