How to protect yourself and others from coronavirus (COVID-19)
To help reduce the spread of COVID-19 and protect those who are most at risk, it is important that you take the recommended steps to protect yourself and others.
If you have COVID-19, wearing a surgical mask can help to prevent spreading it to others.
If you are well, you do not need to wear a surgical mask. There is little evidence that widespread use of surgical masks in healthy people prevents transmission in public.
To help slow the spread of COVID-19, practise good hygiene and social distancing and follow the rules for public gatherings and self-isolation.
Social distancing
Find out how to practise social distancing in public, at home, at work, and in schools.
Self-isolation
Self-isolation means staying at home for 14 days. Find out who must self-isolate and how to self-isolate.
There is no vaccine for COVID-19, but there is one for the flu.
You should get your flu shot when it’s available. Getting the flu and COVID-19 at the same time can make you very ill.
Scientists from around the world are working on developing a vaccine for COVID-19. The World Health Organisation believes this may be available within 18 months.
